      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Cryptocurrency for Beginners: Bitcoin, Ethereum and More</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 8, 2025 • 5 min read</p>

      <p>Cryptocurrency is everywhere in the news, but the jargon around it — blockchain, mining, wallets, DeFi — can make it feel impenetrable. Here is a plain-language introduction to digital currencies and how they work.</p>

      <h2>What is Cryptocurrency?</h2>
      <p>A cryptocurrency is digital money that uses cryptography (mathematical codes) to secure transactions. Unlike traditional currencies issued by governments (USD, EUR, GBP), cryptocurrencies are typically:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Decentralised:</strong> Not controlled by any single government or bank</li>
        <li><strong>Transparent:</strong> All transactions are recorded on a public ledger (blockchain)</li>
        <li><strong>Limited supply:</strong> Most have a maximum number of coins that can ever exist</li>
        <li><strong>Digital-only:</strong> No physical coins or notes</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Major Cryptocurrencies</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bitcoin (BTC):</strong> The original cryptocurrency (2009). Digital gold — primarily used as a store of value. Maximum supply: 21 million coins</li>
        <li><strong>Ethereum (ETH):</strong> A programmable blockchain (2015). Powers smart contracts and decentralised applications. Used for NFTs, DeFi, and more</li>
        <li><strong>Stablecoins (USDT, USDC):</strong> Pegged to traditional currencies (usually $1 each). Used for trading and transfers without volatility</li>
        <li><strong>Others:</strong> Thousands exist with different purposes — payments, privacy, gaming, data storage</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How Does Blockchain Work?</h2>
      <p>Think of a blockchain as a shared spreadsheet that thousands of computers maintain simultaneously:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>You send crypto to someone — this creates a transaction</li>
        <li>The transaction is broadcast to a network of computers (nodes)</li>
        <li>Nodes verify the transaction is valid (you have sufficient funds, no double-spending)</li>
        <li>Verified transactions are grouped into a "block"</li>
        <li>The block is added to the chain permanently — it cannot be altered or deleted</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Key Concepts for Beginners</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wallet:</strong> Software that stores your crypto keys (not the coins themselves — those live on the blockchain)</li>
        <li><strong>Private key:</strong> A secret code that proves you own your crypto. Lose it and you lose access forever</li>
        <li><strong>Mining:</strong> Using computers to validate transactions and earn new coins (Bitcoin uses this)</li>
        <li><strong>Staking:</strong> Locking up your crypto to help validate transactions and earn rewards (Ethereum uses this)</li>
        <li><strong>Exchange:</strong> A platform where you buy, sell, and trade cryptocurrencies</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Risks to Understand</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Volatility:</strong> Prices can swing 10-20% in a single day</li>
        <li><strong>No guarantees:</strong> Unlike bank deposits, crypto is not insured or guaranteed</li>
        <li><strong>Scams:</strong> The space attracts fraudsters — never share your private keys</li>
        <li><strong>Regulation:</strong> Laws around crypto vary by country and are still evolving</li>
        <li><strong>Complexity:</strong> Mistakes (wrong address, lost keys) are usually irreversible</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Cryptocurrency is a rapidly evolving space. Whether you choose to invest or not, understanding the basics helps you make informed decisions in an increasingly digital financial world.</p>

